<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-01-29T16:36:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-01-29T16:36:00-05:00" n="108" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d108">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">714.1515/70: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Guatemala</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Thurston</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Guatemala</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-01-29T15:00:00-06:36"><hi rend="italic">January
                                            29, 1918, 3 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[<hi rend="italic">Received 10.28 p.m.</hi>]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>My telegram of January 28, 12 noon. The Minister for Foreign Affairs
                                called this morning to inform me that the Cuyamel Company’s laborers
                                are armed and continue development work.</p>
                            <p>I have heard that Ocaña left Tegucigalpa because of objectionable
                                treatment and that the departure from here of the Honduranean
                                Minister is due to his having been recalled.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Thurston</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>